## 🐛 Bug Report

StreamBuf.pipe method does not return the destination stream as stream.Readable streams do. This breaks its usage with stream.pipeline calls (might break in other scenarios as well).

Lib version: 4.2.0

## Steps To Reproduce

```javascript
const wb = new ExcelJS.stream.xlsx.WorkbookWriter();
const pass = new stream.PassThrough();

let s = stream.pipeline([
    workbook.stream,
    pass,
], e=>console.error('Pipeline error', e));
expect(!!s);
expect(s).to.equal(pass);
```

## The expected behaviour:

StreamBuf.pipe should return the destination stream.


## Possible solution (optional, but very helpful):

A simple change [here](https://github.com/exceljs/exceljs/blob/e1de62647ff92d64637f8c817f483605a8f69971/lib/utils/stream-buf.js#L342) would fix the issue. Pipe method would look like:

```javascript
pipe(destination) {
    // add destination to pipe list & write current buffer
    this.pipes.push(destination);
    if (!this.paused && this.buffers.length) {
      this.end();
    }
    return destination; // <== added line
},
```

I'm willing to submit a PR for this issue.
